Given below is the update on policy level intervention at workplaces in Bangladesh, India and Sri Lanka.

BANGLADESH:
Meetings were held at both the worksite to discuss policy level intervention. The General Manager of the work site has agreed for display of health messages in the form of posters at the factory premises and at the Head Office. 

INDIA:
The Peer mentors had come up with 26 recommendations for policy level interventions at the work site. This was discussed with Management and shortlisted 8-10 feasible policy level interventions. The first policy level intervention was the display of health messages at workplace in the knowledge portal of their intranet which is accessed by all employees.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>589d9f6eeb36a4.85453649</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Industry/Business</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Health Awareness Talk at the work sites in Bangladesh, India and Sri Lanka</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>ADC67750-6249-485C-A915-C2FA2DEEB63E</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Health Awareness Talk at work sites in Bangladesh, India and Sri Lanka focused on create awareness among the employees at worksite regarding the Cardio Vascular Diseases and its risk factors and how to prevent its occurrence. 
3 sessions covered during the talk as: 1) Why is heart disease, stroke and diabetes increasing in our country and how can we prevent it 2) Why conduct a project to improve health at worksites , 3) What will be done as part of the PROGRESS project at the worksite, and how will it benefit the employees and followed by discussion with the employees. 

Outcome/impact: The health awareness talks were well received by the worksite audience. The session was an interactive one which generally kindled interest about evidence based preventive measures for cardiovascular disease prevention. This interest also resulted in participation in the peer mentor mentored intervention study. There has been increased demand for more health awareness sessions on chronic cardiovascular disease prevention.

BANGLADESH :
1) Held at Sadharan Bima Corporation, Motijheel, Dhaka On 27th October 2015 (3.00pm to 4.30pm)
Attendees from Sadharan Bima Corporation: A total of 50 managerial officers were present at the talk. Majority of them were Managers (24%). Other attendees had various top-level designations such as Deputy Managers (20%), Assistant Managers (22%), Deputy General Managers (10%), Assistant General Managers (8%), General Managers (6%) and others (10%). 
Attendees from icddr,b :Dr. Ashique Haider Chowdhury (Senior Research Investigator and the Principal Investigator of PROGRESS in Bangladesh), Shyfuddin Ahmed (Research Investigator and Coordinator of PROGRESS in Bangladesh) and Syeda Novera Anwar (Research Officer), Cardiologist Dr. M. A. Hasnat, MD 

2) Held at Appollo Ispat Complex Limited, Tejgaon, Dhaka On 17th October 2015 (12.00pm to 1.30pm)
Attendees from Appollo Ispat Complex Limited: The Managing Director (MD) of the company, Md. Ansar Ali, along with the Executive Director, Senior General Manager, General Manager, Senior Manager and Director of the company had attended the talk. A total of 23 senior level employees were present; most of them were Managers of different departments (around 40%). 
Attendees from icddr,b :Dr. Aliya Naheed (Interim Head, Non-Communicable Diseases, under Health Systems and Population Studies), Dr. Ashique Haider Chowdhury (Senior Research Investigator and the Principal Investigator of PROGRESS in Bangladesh), Dr. Ali Tanweer Siddique (Senior Research Investigator and the Co-investigator of PROGRESS in Bangladesh), Shyfuddin Ahmed (Research Investigator and Coordinator of PROGRESS in Bangladesh), Dr. Tauhidul Islam (Research Investigator) and Syeda Novera Anwar (Research Officer) were present to conduct the Health Awareness Talk. icddr,b invited one of its collaborating cardiologist Dr. M. A. Hasnat, MBBS, FCPS(Medicine), MD (Cardiology).

